{
  "texts": [
    "For if M, x ⊩ □ i φ, then by Persistence, for all x ′ ⊑ x we have M, x ′ ⊩ □ i φ, which with ∀x ∃y xR i y implies that there is a y ′ such that x ′ R i y ′ and M, y ′ ⊩ φ,which implies M, x ⊩ ♢ i φ.",
    "Then since M, x ⊩ □ i φ implies M, x ⊩ ♢ i φ, it clearly follows that M, x ⊩ □ i ♢ i □ i □ i p implies M, x ⊩ ♢ i ♢ i □ i ♢ i p. Thus, □ i ♢ i □ i □ i p → ♢ i ♢ i □ i ♢ i p is valid over F.The claim of no local correspondent follows from the fact that the formula The proof of Fact 6.15 also shows that □ i p → ♢ i p globally corresponds to ∀x ∃y xR i y.",
    "In contrast to Fact 6.15, however, it is easy to see that □ i p → ♢ i p locally corresponds to ∀x ⊑ x 0 ∃y xR i y.",
    "This is an atypical case of correspondence, insofar as we can show that if F, x 0 does not satisfy ∀x ⊑ x 0 ∃y xR i y, then for every model M based on F, M, x 0 ⊮ □ i p → ♢ i p. Typically we have to carefully choose a falsifying model.□ i ♢ i □ i □ i p → ♢ i ♢ i □ i ♢ i pIndeed, the tricky part of establishing correspondence is usually that of showing that if F, x ⊩ φ, then F, x satisfies the putative local first-order correspondent ψ(x) of φ, and similarly in the global case.",
    "The direct strategy for local correspondence is to show that we can find minimal valuations π in such a way that from the fact that φ is true at x in the models ⟨F, π⟩ (by the assumption that F, x ⊩ φ), it follows that ψ(x) is satisfied by x in F as a first-order structure."
  ]
